Nevertheless, in this last Latin America’s community there is an issue that may spark further debate. The Commission for the Defense of the Rights of Peoples established Article 21 of the Constitution of Venezuela which states, “That all Venezuela women are free in the exercise of their reproductive rights” (Hellman, 2004). The amendment does not state exactly what the constitutional rights are and thus has left open to interpretation using an article-based, but vague reference to an issue. Further debate about this clause and its legality under international law is important in order to clarify the document in order to deter any potential corruption or abuse.

In Latin America there is no evidence of political Islam. However it is worth noting that “sharia law” has had a voice in recent national debates in Peru, Ecuador, Panama, Honduras, Chile and Argentina (Hellman, 2005). The Panamanian congress has declared that is it illegal for men to “pursue” pregnant women who request an abortion (Hellman, 2005).
